<subSubSection id="D6FEADDA5A5A2521A79888ECFD8AC669" pageId="6" pageNumber="396" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="9E5BFE515A5A2521A79888ECFD7BC7A5" blockId="6.[151,1437,401,2013]" pageId="6" pageNumber="396">
<emphasis id="AC9022435A5A2521A79888ECFED8C781" bold="true" box="[199,334,1664,1689]" pageId="6" pageNumber="396">Etymology.</emphasis>
The epithet ‘nigropilosa’ (from the Latin ‘ 
<emphasis id="AC9022435A5A2521A46888EDFCE5C780" box="[823,883,1665,1688]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="396">nigro</emphasis>
’, black, and the Greek ‘ 
<emphasis id="AC9022435A5A2521A3D688ECFB29C781" box="[1161,1215,1664,1689]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="396">pilos</emphasis>
’, pile) refers to the typical black pile of the body of this singular species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9E5BFE515A5A2521A79888A4FD8AC669" blockId="6.[151,1437,401,2013]" pageId="6" pageNumber="396">
<emphasis id="AC9022435A5A2521A79888A4FE0FC7F9" bold="true" box="[199,409,1736,1761]" pageId="6" pageNumber="396">Taxonomic notes.</emphasis>
Although 
<taxonomicName id="59E485D25A5A2521A54988A5FD2DC7F9" box="[534,699,1736,1761]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Quichuana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigropilosa" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="AC9022435A5A2521A54988A5FD2DC7F9" box="[534,699,1736,1761]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="396">Q. nigropilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="AC9022435A5A2521A59B88A4FC91C7F9" bold="true" box="[708,775,1736,1761]" pageId="6" pageNumber="396">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B7A39F385A5A2521A59B88A4FC91C7F9" box="[708,775,1736,1761]" pageId="6" pageNumber="396" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is described from a single female, we evidenced that the species differs significantly from 
<taxonomicName id="59E485D25A5A2521A5758881FD00C61C" box="[554,662,1773,1796]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Quichuana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="citara" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="AC9022435A5A2521A5758881FD00C61C" box="[554,662,1773,1796]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="396">Q. citara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="AC9022435A5A2521A5FC8880FD7FC61D" bold="true" box="[675,745,1772,1797]" pageId="6" pageNumber="396">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B7A39F385A5A2521A5FC8880FD7FC61D" box="[675,745,1772,1797]" pageId="6" pageNumber="396" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName id="59E485D25A5A2521A5A18881FCFEC61D" box="[766,872,1772,1797]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Quichuana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melas">
<emphasis id="AC9022435A5A2521A5A18881FCFEC61D" box="[766,872,1772,1797]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="396">Q. melas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="59E485D25A5A2521A4F38881FB92C61C" box="[940,1028,1773,1796]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Quichuana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atra">
<emphasis id="AC9022435A5A2521A4F38881FB92C61C" box="[940,1028,1773,1796]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="396">Q. atra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see ‘Taxonomic notes’ under 
<taxonomicName id="59E485D25A5A2521A2DE8881FE81C631" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Quichuana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigropilosa">
<emphasis id="AC9022435A5A2521A2DE8881FE81C631" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="396">Q. nigropilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and Table 1). Another important feature is its restricted distribution, which raises the need for further expeditions to neighboring areas of the 
<typeStatus id="415F40F35A5A2521A50B8959FD12C655" box="[596,644,1845,1869]" pageId="6" pageNumber="396">type</typeStatus>
locality, in order to increase the knowledge about species distribution, as well as finding male specimens.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
